WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.179 --> 00:00:02.929
(pensive music)

2
00:00:07.987 --> 00:00:09.000
<v Announcer>Dr. Beste is here</v>

3
00:00:09.000 --> 00:00:11.160
to talk about something important,

4
00:00:11.160 --> 00:00:13.020
which is well-child care.

5
00:00:13.020 --> 00:00:16.680
And she is an expert on adolescent care

6
00:00:16.680 --> 00:00:19.157
'cause she has emerging adults now in her family.

7
00:00:19.157 --> 00:00:20.820
<v Dr. Beste>I have emerging adults now.</v>

8
00:00:20.820 --> 00:00:22.017
<v Announcer>Okay, take it over Jan. Thank you.</v>

9
00:00:22.017 --> 00:00:23.310
<v ->For those of you who don't know,</v>

10
00:00:23.310 --> 00:00:25.710
after adolescence, they are now emerging adults.

11
00:00:25.710 --> 00:00:28.710
Those 18 to 26 year olds, so to speak.

12
00:00:28.710 --> 00:00:30.000
Okay, so we're gonna talk about kids.

13
00:00:30.000 --> 00:00:32.370
I still have nothing to disclose.

14
00:00:32.370 --> 00:00:35.160
Here are our learning objectives, so we're gonna get going.

15
00:00:35.160 --> 00:00:36.780
So the well-child visit,

16
00:00:36.780 --> 00:00:38.010
what do we do at the well-child visit?

17
00:00:38.010 --> 00:00:39.667
If you ask parents, they're going to say,

18
00:00:39.667 --> 00:00:40.980
"Well, they're there for shots."

19
00:00:40.980 --> 00:00:42.900
Well, there's obviously a lot more than just shots.

20
00:00:42.900 --> 00:00:43.830
You're doing history.

21
00:00:43.830 --> 00:00:45.240
You're doing growth and development.

22
00:00:45.240 --> 00:00:46.560
You're doing your physical.

23
00:00:46.560 --> 00:00:48.510
You're doing all kinds of health screenings.

24
00:00:48.510 --> 00:00:50.040
And then you also are doing vaccines,

25
00:00:50.040 --> 00:00:53.580
as well as advising the parents as to what to expect next.

26
00:00:53.580 --> 00:00:55.530
So let's start with our first question.

27
00:00:56.640 --> 00:00:59.160
You are performing a developmental examination

28
00:00:59.160 --> 00:01:00.960
on an 18-month-old boy.

29
00:01:00.960 --> 00:01:04.650
Which of the following would be abnormal for this age group?

30
00:01:04.650 --> 00:01:07.260
That he only scribbles when given a crayon?

31
00:01:07.260 --> 00:01:09.150
That he can drink from a cup?

32
00:01:09.150 --> 00:01:12.030
That he just babbles and imitates sounds?

33
00:01:12.030 --> 00:01:14.373
Or that he can stack two blocks?

34
00:01:20.250 --> 00:01:21.540
All right. Yes, good!

35
00:01:21.540 --> 00:01:23.730
Most of you realize that a child who's only babbling

36
00:01:23.730 --> 00:01:25.890
and imitating sounds an 18 month old,

37
00:01:25.890 --> 00:01:27.300
that is not normal.

38
00:01:27.300 --> 00:01:29.160
So I'm not gonna go through all of these in detail,

39
00:01:29.160 --> 00:01:32.250
but I do encourage you to review them.

40
00:01:32.250 --> 00:01:34.560
Mostly you really wanna focus on the verbal

41
00:01:34.560 --> 00:01:36.210
and gross motor developments.

42
00:01:36.210 --> 00:01:38.550
Those seem to be the ones that come up pretty frequently

43
00:01:38.550 --> 00:01:39.930
on the boards.

44
00:01:39.930 --> 00:01:41.670
Mostly remembering that two months of age

45
00:01:41.670 --> 00:01:44.700
is when they start smiling and start vocalizing,

46
00:01:44.700 --> 00:01:46.290
which is what saves their lives, by the way,

47
00:01:46.290 --> 00:01:48.780
'cause that's when colic also happens.

48
00:01:48.780 --> 00:01:49.950
By the time they're six months,

49
00:01:49.950 --> 00:01:54.950
they should be able to sit up and not have any head lag.

50
00:01:55.200 --> 00:01:56.040
By nine months,

51
00:01:56.040 --> 00:01:57.870
they should be able to sit completely without support.

52
00:01:57.870 --> 00:02:00.630
They can start standing and cruising.

53
00:02:00.630 --> 00:02:03.390
And this is when they start doing the dada, mama.

54
00:02:03.390 --> 00:02:07.260
By one year of age, they should start to walk,

55
00:02:07.260 --> 00:02:09.630
at least walk with help, standing alone.

56
00:02:09.630 --> 00:02:11.930
They start babbling, so this is that babbling.

57
00:02:13.050 --> 00:02:15.660
They should respond to no.

58
00:02:15.660 --> 00:02:16.890
Doesn't mean that they stopped doing,

59
00:02:16.890 --> 00:02:20.310
but they should at least be like, "Mom just said no."

60
00:02:20.310 --> 00:02:23.130
So at 18 months, they can walk backwards.

61
00:02:23.130 --> 00:02:24.630
They can speak three to six words.

62
00:02:24.630 --> 00:02:26.340
This is a good milestone to know.

63
00:02:26.340 --> 00:02:27.720
They can stack those two blocks

64
00:02:27.720 --> 00:02:30.540
and understand simple commands by two years of age.

65
00:02:30.540 --> 00:02:33.720
As toddlers, they can speak 50 words,

66
00:02:33.720 --> 00:02:36.690
put two words together, and understand a two-part command.

67
00:02:36.690 --> 00:02:38.790
That's a good one to remember.

68
00:02:38.790 --> 00:02:41.310
They should know six body parts, stack four blocks.

69
00:02:41.310 --> 00:02:42.780
They take off their clothes,

70
00:02:42.780 --> 00:02:45.390
frequently, in inappropriate settings.

71
00:02:45.390 --> 00:02:46.800
By three years of age,

72
00:02:46.800 --> 00:02:48.660
they can understand what hungry and tired is.

73
00:02:48.660 --> 00:02:50.790
They can name four pictures.

74
00:02:50.790 --> 00:02:51.870
They can pedal a tricycle.

75
00:02:51.870 --> 00:02:53.700
And they ask, "Why?"

76
00:02:53.700 --> 00:02:56.940
So two years of age, it's know why.

77
00:02:56.940 --> 00:02:57.773
One of the great things,

78
00:02:57.773 --> 00:02:59.400
both my husband and I are doctors,

79
00:02:59.400 --> 00:03:01.410
about us both being doctors is when our kids asked

80
00:03:01.410 --> 00:03:03.000
why we gave them really long,

81
00:03:03.000 --> 00:03:05.280
lengthy scientific explanations.

82
00:03:05.280 --> 00:03:07.440
So that phase didn't last very long in our house.

83
00:03:07.440 --> 00:03:10.590
So by four years, they become a cute little kid.

84
00:03:10.590 --> 00:03:11.850
They're getting ready to go to kindergarten,

85
00:03:11.850 --> 00:03:14.310
so they should be able to name four colors,

86
00:03:14.310 --> 00:03:15.510
know their first and last name.

87
00:03:15.510 --> 00:03:17.670
They can go up and down stairs, alternating feet.

88
00:03:17.670 --> 00:03:19.260
They can draw a circle.

89
00:03:19.260 --> 00:03:20.790
They're super fun at that age.

90
00:03:20.790 --> 00:03:21.870
Okay, so some of the things

91
00:03:21.870 --> 00:03:24.060
that are recommended in this age group.

92
00:03:24.060 --> 00:03:27.090
So autism spectrum disorder screening is recommended

93
00:03:27.090 --> 00:03:28.710
by the American Academy of Pediatrics.

94
00:03:28.710 --> 00:03:31.470
It is an I recommendation by USPSTF.

95
00:03:31.470 --> 00:03:32.303
Don't panic.

96
00:03:32.303 --> 00:03:33.780
I have a nice little chart

97
00:03:33.780 --> 00:03:37.500
where the AAP differs from the USPSTF.

98
00:03:37.500 --> 00:03:40.590
You'll never be asked, you know, one of those things.

99
00:03:40.590 --> 00:03:41.820
But just for your own interest,

100
00:03:41.820 --> 00:03:43.710
which ones are recommended by which?

101
00:03:43.710 --> 00:03:45.780
So autism, whoa, look at this:

102
00:03:45.780 --> 00:03:48.840
More prevalent in siblings of autistic children.

103
00:03:48.840 --> 00:03:51.600
Early interventions have been shown to improve outcomes.

104
00:03:51.600 --> 00:03:54.180
So let's move on to USPSTF recommendations.

105
00:03:54.180 --> 00:03:56.880
There are no A recommendations in this age group.

106
00:03:56.880 --> 00:03:58.710
Ooh, but there's a whole bunch of B recommendations.

107
00:03:58.710 --> 00:04:01.740
So B recommendations I would pay attention to:

108
00:04:01.740 --> 00:04:03.600
The first couple are about fluoride.

109
00:04:03.600 --> 00:04:04.590
So oral fluoride,

110
00:04:04.590 --> 00:04:07.590
if the fluoride is low in their water supply,

111
00:04:07.590 --> 00:04:10.230
remembering that even if they have city water

112
00:04:10.230 --> 00:04:11.550
or well water with fluoride,

113
00:04:11.550 --> 00:04:12.810
they may not be drinking it.

114
00:04:12.810 --> 00:04:14.580
I've been impressed with the number of families

115
00:04:14.580 --> 00:04:16.740
that only drink bottled water without fluoride.

116
00:04:16.740 --> 00:04:17.573
So ask about that.

117
00:04:17.573 --> 00:04:20.040
So we want oral fluoride supplementation.

118
00:04:20.040 --> 00:04:22.530
Put fluoride application on their teeth.

119
00:04:22.530 --> 00:04:24.450
Vision screening for all children once

120
00:04:24.450 --> 00:04:25.620
between the ages of three to five

121
00:04:25.620 --> 00:04:27.360
to detect amblyopia.

122
00:04:27.360 --> 00:04:28.380
Obesity screening.

123
00:04:28.380 --> 00:04:29.490
We'll talk about that a little bit more.

124
00:04:29.490 --> 00:04:31.230
And skin cancer prevention counseling.

125
00:04:31.230 --> 00:04:33.270
I live at the beach in North Carolina.

126
00:04:33.270 --> 00:04:34.920
I fight on this one all the time.

127
00:04:34.920 --> 00:04:36.750
Put some sunscreen on your kids.

128
00:04:36.750 --> 00:04:38.250
Okay, this may be new for some of you

129
00:04:38.250 --> 00:04:39.990
if you haven't taken care of kids for a while.

130
00:04:39.990 --> 00:04:44.700
One of the new USPSTF recommendations is to screen the moms

131
00:04:44.700 --> 00:04:46.860
for maternal depression at the 1, 2, 4,

132
00:04:46.860 --> 00:04:48.660
and 6 month well-child visits.

133
00:04:48.660 --> 00:04:51.480
Most of you are using PHQ-9s in your office.

134
00:04:51.480 --> 00:04:52.313
You can use that.

135
00:04:52.313 --> 00:04:53.146
If you want to,

136
00:04:53.146 --> 00:04:55.500
you can use the Edinburgh Postnatal Depression Scale,

137
00:04:55.500 --> 00:04:57.780
but you should be doing that in some states.

138
00:04:57.780 --> 00:05:00.960
In North Carolina, we actually get paid for it.

139
00:05:00.960 --> 00:05:01.793
Dental caries.

140
00:05:01.793 --> 00:05:02.820
So we talked about fluoride.

141
00:05:02.820 --> 00:05:04.980
Dental caries are the most common chronic disease

142
00:05:04.980 --> 00:05:05.813
of young children.

143
00:05:05.813 --> 00:05:08.322
So when parents ask, you should brush their teeth

144
00:05:08.322 --> 00:05:11.482
with fluoride toothpaste twice a day,

145
00:05:11.482 --> 00:05:13.860
rice-sized amount until they're at age two,

146
00:05:13.860 --> 00:05:15.090
then a pea-sized amount.

147
00:05:15.090 --> 00:05:16.710
I think that's helpful for parents to understand

148
00:05:16.710 --> 00:05:17.730
how much to put on.

149
00:05:17.730 --> 00:05:19.500
Floss as soon as the teeth are touching.

150
00:05:19.500 --> 00:05:21.500
They should have a dentist by age three.

151
00:05:22.470 --> 00:05:24.030
Here's a nice little handy-dandy chart.

152
00:05:24.030 --> 00:05:26.580
Again, you can use Dr. Google to find this chart

153
00:05:26.580 --> 00:05:28.620
from the American Academy of Pediatric Dentistry

154
00:05:28.620 --> 00:05:29.550
if you need to.

155
00:05:29.550 --> 00:05:30.840
Okay, somebody asked

156
00:05:30.840 --> 00:05:35.840
at the last talk about pediatric screening for eye vision.

157
00:05:36.030 --> 00:05:38.910
So here are your recommendations

158
00:05:38.910 --> 00:05:40.410
for referring if their visual acuity

159
00:05:40.410 --> 00:05:44.130
is less than 20/40 by three or 20/30 by age five:

160
00:05:44.130 --> 00:05:46.140
Anytime you have asymmetry.

161
00:05:46.140 --> 00:05:48.960
Or if they have quotes, "a lazy eye,"

162
00:05:48.960 --> 00:05:52.908
strabismus at 3 to 6 months.

163
00:05:52.908 --> 00:05:55.080
And any abnormal red reflex.

164
00:05:55.080 --> 00:05:58.110
So this is why amblyopia due to strabismus,

165
00:05:58.110 --> 00:05:59.040
so that lazy eye,

166
00:05:59.040 --> 00:06:00.150
so if you're looking at their eye

167
00:06:00.150 --> 00:06:03.060
and one eye is drifting when you do the cover on cover test,

168
00:06:03.060 --> 00:06:06.330
it's a leading cause of monocular vision loss in children.

169
00:06:06.330 --> 00:06:07.380
So the recommendation

170
00:06:07.380 --> 00:06:11.042
is that you should do the official screening at age four.

171
00:06:11.042 --> 00:06:12.540
It's where you have 'em,

172
00:06:12.540 --> 00:06:13.980
you know, stand and look at the vision chart

173
00:06:13.980 --> 00:06:17.850
and try to tell you what all those pictures are.

174
00:06:17.850 --> 00:06:20.040
Instrument-based is the, you know, looking in their eyes

175
00:06:20.040 --> 00:06:21.720
with your ophthalmoscope,

176
00:06:21.720 --> 00:06:23.190
doing the cover on cover time,

177
00:06:23.190 --> 00:06:25.680
making sure that the eyes stay straight.

178
00:06:25.680 --> 00:06:27.240
Obesity screening.

179
00:06:27.240 --> 00:06:29.910
This is I think my favorite screening recommendation.

180
00:06:29.910 --> 00:06:31.530
They say you should screen for obesity

181
00:06:31.530 --> 00:06:34.770
in children and adolescents greater than six years of age.

182
00:06:34.770 --> 00:06:36.540
And you should offer/refer them

183
00:06:36.540 --> 00:06:39.510
to comprehensive, intensive behavioral interventions

184
00:06:39.510 --> 00:06:42.090
greater than 25 hours of face-to-face, family-based,

185
00:06:42.090 --> 00:06:44.280
multi-component treatment over 3 to 12 months

186
00:06:44.280 --> 00:06:46.110
to promote improvements in weight.

187
00:06:46.110 --> 00:06:49.530
I don't know about you, but I have no access to that.

188
00:06:49.530 --> 00:06:52.770
So just be aware that is the recommendation.

189
00:06:52.770 --> 00:06:54.720
That's because almost 20% of children

190
00:06:54.720 --> 00:06:56.970
and adolescents are obese,

191
00:06:56.970 --> 00:07:00.660
and a third of children in this country are overweight.

192
00:07:00.660 --> 00:07:03.810
And that number stabilized a little bit lately.

193
00:07:03.810 --> 00:07:05.700
Why do we care about obesity in children?

194
00:07:05.700 --> 00:07:08.208
There's mental health issues, asthma,

195
00:07:08.208 --> 00:07:10.470
obstructive sleep apnea has worsened,

196
00:07:10.470 --> 00:07:11.580
they have orthopedic problems,

197
00:07:11.580 --> 00:07:14.190
and of course all the cardiovascular metabolic

198
00:07:14.190 --> 00:07:15.540
things that we think about.

199
00:07:17.130 --> 00:07:19.200
And also, particularly in this age group,

200
00:07:19.200 --> 00:07:22.290
they really have a lot of weight-based victimization.

201
00:07:22.290 --> 00:07:23.550
Not to say that adults don't,

202
00:07:23.550 --> 00:07:25.830
but it's really cruel in this age group.

203
00:07:25.830 --> 00:07:27.600
And obesity in childhood and adolescents

204
00:07:27.600 --> 00:07:29.130
may continue into adulthood.

205
00:07:29.130 --> 00:07:29.963
And then you have

206
00:07:29.963 --> 00:07:33.120
all of the associated cardiovascular issues

207
00:07:33.120 --> 00:07:34.140
that we know about.

208
00:07:34.140 --> 00:07:35.670
This is kind of just a fun little thing.

209
00:07:35.670 --> 00:07:39.150
If a child drinks more than five cans of soda a day

210
00:07:39.150 --> 00:07:40.770
or is active less than one hour a day,

211
00:07:40.770 --> 00:07:41.670
their risk increases.

212
00:07:41.670 --> 00:07:45.030
So that's kind of a nice easy thing you can ask.

213
00:07:45.030 --> 00:07:47.220
Don't drink five cans of soda a day.

214
00:07:47.220 --> 00:07:49.350
And of course, like everything else,

215
00:07:49.350 --> 00:07:51.600
significant racial and ethnic disparities exist

216
00:07:51.600 --> 00:07:53.940
with our Hispanic children having the highest rates

217
00:07:53.940 --> 00:07:56.540
followed closely by our non-Hispanic Black children.

218
00:07:57.540 --> 00:07:59.520
There are no D recommendations in this age group.

219
00:07:59.520 --> 00:08:00.990
Okay, so I recommendations.

220
00:08:00.990 --> 00:08:04.080
You do not need to know all of the I recommendations.

221
00:08:04.080 --> 00:08:05.400
There are a couple of them

222
00:08:05.400 --> 00:08:08.640
that differ from the American Academy of Pediatrics,

223
00:08:08.640 --> 00:08:09.473
and I will go through those.

224
00:08:09.473 --> 00:08:13.140
I put 'em in orange, but I also made this cool little chart.

225
00:08:13.140 --> 00:08:15.930
So if you notice that the American Academy of Pediatrics

226
00:08:15.930 --> 00:08:18.840
recommends that you screen for iron deficiency anemia,

227
00:08:18.840 --> 00:08:21.810
whereas USPSTF makes out an I recommendation,

228
00:08:21.810 --> 00:08:24.630
the AAP recommends the screening for lipids.

229
00:08:24.630 --> 00:08:25.860
This does come up on the board,

230
00:08:25.860 --> 00:08:27.270
so I would make sure that you pay attention

231
00:08:27.270 --> 00:08:29.250
to the AAP recommendation.

232
00:08:29.250 --> 00:08:30.960
Risk-based screening at 2, 4, and 6 years,

233
00:08:30.960 --> 00:08:34.307
but universal screening in the school age years 9 to 11,

234
00:08:34.307 --> 00:08:36.510
and 17 to 21.

235
00:08:36.510 --> 00:08:38.460
Screening for hypertension.

236
00:08:38.460 --> 00:08:40.800
And use of a brief formal screening instrument

237
00:08:40.800 --> 00:08:43.350
to detect speech language delay up to age five,

238
00:08:43.350 --> 00:08:48.090
recommended by the AAP, a I recommendation by USPSTF.

239
00:08:48.090 --> 00:08:49.830
Briefly, just about anemia affects

240
00:08:49.830 --> 00:08:52.080
about 50% of children worldwide.

241
00:08:52.080 --> 00:08:53.310
By far, in the United States,

242
00:08:53.310 --> 00:08:55.200
the most common cause is iron deficiency.

243
00:08:55.200 --> 00:08:56.370
Remember what I said earlier

244
00:08:56.370 --> 00:08:58.890
about supplementing your kids with iron

245
00:08:58.890 --> 00:09:01.020
in that first year of life.

246
00:09:01.020 --> 00:09:03.000
And because it's so common in this country,

247
00:09:03.000 --> 00:09:06.060
the recommendation is if you detect anemia,

248
00:09:06.060 --> 00:09:08.250
put them on some iron, recheck it in a month.

249
00:09:08.250 --> 00:09:09.900
If it goes up by one gram,

250
00:09:09.900 --> 00:09:12.360
it's probably iron deficiency anemia.

251
00:09:12.360 --> 00:09:14.040
If it doesn't, first of all,

252
00:09:14.040 --> 00:09:15.300
make sure the parents gave it to them.

253
00:09:15.300 --> 00:09:18.210
I would say the highest percentage of patients

254
00:09:18.210 --> 00:09:19.777
that don't get better because the parent's like,

255
00:09:19.777 --> 00:09:22.170
"Eh, I really didn't think it was that important."

256
00:09:22.170 --> 00:09:23.310
So just make sure the parents gave it to 'em.

257
00:09:23.310 --> 00:09:25.610
If not, then you need to look at other causes.

258
00:09:26.490 --> 00:09:28.200
And obviously, if you're starting to look

259
00:09:28.200 --> 00:09:30.000
in normocytic or macrocytic anemia,

260
00:09:30.000 --> 00:09:33.240
you gotta go through a much more intense evaluation.

261
00:09:33.240 --> 00:09:34.290
Okay, next question.

262
00:09:34.290 --> 00:09:36.780
So you have a mother who brings her 9-month-old daughter in

263
00:09:36.780 --> 00:09:38.070
for her routine visit.

264
00:09:38.070 --> 00:09:39.270
So which of the following

265
00:09:39.270 --> 00:09:42.150
